  <text>
    <body>
      <div type="introduction">
        <p>This manuscript copy of the text of Bel seems to have originally been copied over by a
          single scribe. This single scribe’s work was then edited at an unknown point in time, with
          visibly different hands writing in the margins and reintroducing dropped/skipped over
          words. These corrections within Bel are always minor, never changing the meaning of the
          text. The textual features might indicate the particular way the scribe spoke, as the
          letter nu (ν) is dropped far more frequently than any other letter, with epsilon, the next
          most frequently dropped letter far behind. However, that is ultimately just pure
          conjecture. The purpose of this edition of the text is to introduce another source within
          the textual history of the apocryphal additions to Daniel to a wider audience of scholars
          than those who previously had access to it, and to allow those scholars who did have
          access to it some easier reading. It is this accessibility and readability informed
          approach which most informed this edition of the text, which was also buttressed by an
          interest in accuracy to the original manuscript. It is worthy of note that in service of
          readability, where an individual word crosses over from one line to the next, a hyphen has
          been added, and is indicated as being an addition by the current editors by its orange
          hue. The transcription employed was not intended to be 1:1, and curious textual variants
          such as individual words not found in other editions of the text (e.g. Ziegler’s or
          Swete’s editions of the text) were contained. When I say that it was not intended to be
          1:1, what is meant is that scribal idiosyncrasies such as nu-dropping at the end of a line
          were not retained. Swete’s edition of the text was used as a base-text to pull text from,
          which was then compared to and altered to conform to the Codex Marchalianus manuscript.
          Ziegler’s edition of the text was used for the purposes of versification, and the
          punctuation contained within Ziegler was imposed upon the critical edition of the text to
          improve readability. </p>
      </div>
    </body>
